  "local_port": 50304,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My sister was forcefully asked to resign just because she was on bench for a month after her training. How can I fight this injustice?",
  "response": "I'm sorry to hear about your sister's situation. Here are some steps you could consider taking to address the issue:\n\n1. **Understand the Employment Contract:**\n   - Review her employment contract and any related documents to understand her rights and obligations, as well as the employer's policies regarding being on the bench and termination.\n\n2. **Gather Information:**\n   - Collect any relevant documents, emails, or correspondence that might provide context or evidence regarding her resignation and the circumstances leading up to it.\n\n3. **Consult with HR:**\n   - If she hasn't done so already, have her schedule a meeting with the Human Resources department to discuss the situation and seek clarification on the reason for her forced resignation. Document this interaction.\n\n4. **Seek Legal Advice:**\n   - Contact an employment lawyer or legal professional who specializes in labor laws. They can provide guidance on her rights and the legal options available based on local employment laws.\n\n5. **File a Complaint:**\n   - If there are grounds, consider filing a complaint with the relevant labor or employment authorities. They can investigate the situation and determine if there were any legal violations.\n\n6. **Support Networks:**\n   - Encourage your sister to reach out to professional networks, labor unions (if applicable), or employee support groups for advice and support.\n\n7. **Negotiate Severance:**\n   - If applicable, discuss the possibility of negotiating a severance package to ensure she receives some financial support while searching for new employment.\n\n8. **Prepare for New Opportunities:**\n   - Assist her in updating her resume and LinkedIn profile, and support her job search efforts as she looks for a new position.\n\nRemember that employment laws can vary significantly depending on the jurisdiction, so it's important to consult with a legal professional who can provide guidance specific to your sister's situation.",
